<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><listPerson xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><person xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="BON03" sex="1"><persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><roleName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/><forename xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">John Augustus</forename><surname xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Bonney</surname><addName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/></persName><birth xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1000"><placeName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"> </placeName></birth><death xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1813-12-30"/><occupation xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/><note xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="editorial"><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">John Bonney was a lawyer and a member of the Society for Constitutional Information. He was a longtime friend and supporter of John Horne Tooke and was
       arrested with him on a charge of high treason on 16 May 1794. He was later discharged after the acquittal of Tooke, Hardy and Thelwall. 
       In 1796 he supported Tooke in his bid for the 
